<FIRST>r a PM-EXP--Voyager'sEyes     07-02 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EXP--Voyager's Eyes,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Telescopes Around The World Watch Voyager Signals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-EXP--Voyager-Neptune</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT MYGATT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINS OF SAN AUGUSTIN, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Imagine a 20-watt refrigerator light bulb burning in the dark, 2.75 billion miles away. Now imagine the sophisticated eyes needed to see the light. Voyager 2, heading for <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>, is emitting 20 watts of radio signals, information coded in binary bits _ ones and zeros _ on the space probe's health and from its scientific instruments and cameras. `` Think of that lightbulb as flickering, and that flickering contains the information that <PERSON> Voyager </PERSON> is sending back to us,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON>, Voyager preparation manager for the Very Large Array radio telescope. The signals have become fainter since Voyager's encounters with Jupiter in 1979, <ORGANIZATION> Saturn </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 and Uranus in 1986. The signals, and commands sent to the 12-year-old probe, take four hours and six minutes to cross 2.75 billion miles at the speed of light. Larger antennas and more sensitive receivers are needed on Earth to receive the signals, and more power is needed to transmit commands to the craft, which will pass fly within 3,000 miles of <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION> on Aug. 24. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s Deep Space Network is used to talk to Voyager. The DSN has three complexes: <PERSON> Goldstone </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mojave </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>; and Tidbinbilla, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>. When Voyager flew by Uranus, the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and Australian listening posts used three antenna dishes each _ one 210 feet across and two 112 feet _ and the <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> station used one of each, said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Murrill </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Propulsion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION> complex also was linked to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>'s 210-foot <ORGANIZATION> Parkes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astronomy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telescope </ORGANIZATION>. For <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>, the 210-foot dishes at <LOCATION> Goldstone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> have been increased to 230 feet and another 112-foot antenna was built at <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> VLA </ORGANIZATION> is being used in conjunction with <PERSON> Goldstone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Parkes </PERSON> again is linked with <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>, and a Japanese telescope will be added to the network. The different sites ensure that at least one station can communicate with the spacecraft despite the Earth's rotation, <PERSON> Brundage </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> VLA </LOCATION> alone gives us almost a third more images than if we did n't have it,'' said <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Haynes </PERSON>, Voyager project manager at <ORGANIZATION> JPL </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> VLA </ORGANIZATION> is a one-of-a-kind space-age erector set sitting on an ancient lake bed. The site is skirted by four mountain ranges, protecting it from much of the electronic interference from television, radios, aircraft and the like. It consists of 27 white dish-shaped antennas, each 82 feet in diameter, 92 feet high and weighing 235 tons. The dishes sit on the Plains of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Augustin </LOCATION> amid tumbleweed, cattle and sparse vegetation at an altitude of 7,000 feet. The dishes are arranged along three arms of railroad track, laid out in the shape of a Y. Two arms are 13 miles long and the third is 11.8 miles. The Earth rotates the Y like a turntable, creating images that have the same detail as if using a radio telescope up to 26 miles in diameter. A special 36-wheel transporter moves each antenna to one of 72 observation stations along the three arms. This acts like a zoom lens _ the farther out the dishes, the higher the resolution; the closer in, the larger the field of view. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spent $ 6.5 million to equip each dish to receive Voyager's signals It also set up special techniques and installed two big diesel generators to guard against lightning-caused power fluctuations during the thunderstorm season. The separation of the listening posts around the world _ just like the separation of the <ORGANIZATION> VLA </ORGANIZATION> dishes _ strengthen the sensitivity of the network. The signal <ORGANIZATION> VLA </ORGANIZATION> gets from Voyager is sent via satellite to <PERSON> Goldstone </PERSON>, where the two signals are combined, decoded and sent via microwave to <ORGANIZATION> JPL </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
