<HEAD>35 Soldiers A Year Commit Suicide In The Israeli Army</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 35 soldiers in the Israeli army commit suicide each year, the head of the army's personnel department said in a newspaper interview published Sunday. Thirty-two soldiers committed suicide from April 1988 to April 1989, Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Matan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vilnai </PERSON> told the daily <ORGANIZATION> Haaretz </ORGANIZATION>. The military command confirmed the figures. <PERSON> Vilnai </PERSON>'s interview was a departure from the military's customary reluctance to provide such data, which could have a negative effect on soldiers' morale. No figures on attempted suicides were given. The newspaper and army said the average of 35 suicides was for recent years, but they did not say which years. Neither <PERSON> Vilnai </PERSON> nor the military command knew if any of the suicides were related to the 18-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vilnai </PERSON> said 30 percent of those who killed themselves were reservists troubled by family and financial problems. They are pushed into the act by the availability of weapons and the hope that relatives will get financial compensation from the army, he said. Israeli men are drafted at the age of 18 for a three-year period of regular duty, and serve up to 40 days a year as reservists until age 55. Women are drafted for two years of regular service, and some of them are required to serve as reservists afterward. The Tel Aviv-based <ORGANIZATION> Jaffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> says <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has a 170,000-strong standing army and 370,000 reserves. <PERSON> Vilnai </PERSON> said an average of two to three female soldiers commit suicide every year. He said most of the regular soldiers who have killed themselves did so during the first year of their military duty. <ORGANIZATION> Haaretz </ORGANIZATION> said the army's personnel department recently issued instructions on how to spot troubled soldiers to prevent suicides. However, the paper said `` This activity is quite limited since it is feared that dealing with the question of suicide may in fact increase the number of suicides.''
