<BYLINE>By CHET BROKAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT RUSHMORE NATIONAL MEMORIAL, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, celebrated in stone on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rushmore </LOCATION> 50 years ago, should be celebrated today for his environmental spirit, <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said Sunday. `` We're not here just to talk about stewardship of our natural resources. ... We're here to act,'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> told an estimated 4,000 to 5,000 people who turned out to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the unveiling of <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION>'s face on the monument. As the audience sang along with a military band that played `` God <LOCATION> Bless </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' a song introduced at the original dedication of <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION>'s chiseled face 50 years ago, a 90-by-45-foot <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag that had been hung on the mountain was drawn back to reveal the sculpture once again. When sculptor <PERSON> Gutzon </PERSON> <PERSON> Borglum </PERSON> decided <ORGANIZATION> Roosevelt </ORGANIZATION>'s features would be carved next to the 60-foot-tall faces of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, many people wondered if <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> really belonged with the other presidents on the granite mountain. But <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> and other speakers said <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> was a good choice for the huge sculpture known as the <ORGANIZATION> Shrine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> because he was a president for the common person and a leader in the conservation movement. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s administration is dedicated to protecting the environment by reducing acid rain, reversing damage to the ozone layer, restoring wetland nesting areas for waterfowl and protecting endangered species. The administration will work to promote the nation's economic growth, but not at the expense of the environment, said the <ORGANIZATION> interior </ORGANIZATION> secretary, who played key roles in environmental legislation during two decades in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` Make no mistake about it: Our commitment to conserving our natural resources ... will never be sacrificed to corporate profit,'' he said. The huge red, white and blue flag was not placed in front of the sculpture as scheduled at dawn because of wind gusting to 35 mph. A crew of workers on the mountain raised the 300-pound banner for the first time at mid-morning, quickly lowering it because the wind was too strong, threatening their safety and the flag itself. The program stayed on schedule as winds dropped and work crews hoisted the flag into position during the speeches, which were given in the ampitheater at the base of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rushmore </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> said it was fitting that <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> was honored on the mountain because he traveled extensively in the territory that would become the state of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> several decades before becoming president in 1901. Roosevelt first arrived in the 1880s to hunt and buy ranch land in the area that later became <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> said. The governor said <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>'s travels in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> led to his later efforts to conserve the nation's resources and to place more than 100 million acres of forest land into the public trust. `` He knew that somehow, the hills and forests we love so much must be protected for future generations,'' <PERSON> Mickelson </PERSON> said.
