<HEAD>Ten Killed in Syrian Shelling and Inter-Shiite Gun Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at bottom to UPDATE with two Israeli-allied militiamen
wounded in south. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian gunners blasted the Christian sector of the Lebanese capital with shellfire Sunday, and rival militias backed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> clashed in street battles in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, police said. Ten people were killed and 29 wounded, they said. A Soviet envoy and the foreign ministers of three Arab countries working for a settlement of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war arrived in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. Since the latest round of fighting began in March, 396 people have been killed and 1,532 wounded. Police said eight people were killed Sunday and 20 wounded in the Syrian bombardment of Christian east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s sprawling residential districts of <LOCATION> Ashrafiyeh </LOCATION> and Furn el-Shubbak. One shell crashed into the bedroom of <PERSON> Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Abi-Aad </PERSON>, 31, a <ORGANIZATION> Maronite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priest, and his wife <PERSON> Renee </PERSON>, 24, in <LOCATION> Ashrafiyeh </LOCATION>. They were killed as they slept, said a police spokesman, who can not be named under standing rules. The Syrians also pounded a 25-mile coastal stretch to prevent food, fuel and arms supplies from reaching the Christian enclave north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, police said. Christian militia gunners responded with intermittent barrages of 155mm shellfire. The police spokesman said two people were killed and nine wounded in the fighting between the Moslem militias. The gun battles raged all night and through Sunday morning between the Syrian-backed Shiite Moslem Amal militia and the pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or party of God. It was the first major clash between the factions since the death of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s revolutionary patriarch <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> on June 3. The fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> and the more secular <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> have been fighting for control of the million-strong Shiite community, the largest single sect in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The latest round of fighting in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s civil war broke out on March 8 between army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s 20,000 troops, most of them Christians, and an alliance of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s 40,000 troops and Druse forces. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> had stayed out of that confrontation. Soviet envoy <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Bessmertnykh </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> after winning a pledge from <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>'s government, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s main Arab foe, to halt arms shipments to the Lebanese Christians if the Syrians stopped their daily bombardment of the Christian enclave. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Thawra </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> pledge was `` a maneuver ... to mislead the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> committee.'' <PERSON> Bessmertnykh </PERSON> carried a message from Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to Syrian President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON>, said a Soviet source who spoke on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> have close ties with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The Soviets were <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s main arms suppliers during the eight-year Iran-Iraq war, and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s leading Arab ally. The Arab League committee includes <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendjedid </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>. The 22-nation <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> has asked the committee to find a settlement to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s war by November. But so far it has been unable to enforce even a cease-fire called in May. The foreign ministers of the three countries were in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> to discuss the truce violations. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> lashed out at the Arab committee for keeping silent on Syrian violations of the cease-fire. `` The Arab committee is becoming a helpless spectator while the Syrians persist in their daily defiance of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire calls. This is pushing the Lebanese to despair,'' he said in a statement broadcast by Christian radio stations. `` If the Arab League, which is supported by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, is incapable of making the Syrians respect its resolutions, then it must declare the Syrians as the defiers,'' <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> entered <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> under a 1976 <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> mandate to halt the civil war. Christians say the <ORGANIZATION> Syrians </ORGANIZATION> lost their role as neutral peacekeepers because they have sided with Moslems in the civil war. Meanwhile, in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, two militiamen of the Israeli-backed <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lebanon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> were wounded Sunday when their armored personnel carrier hit a mine, police reported. A police spokesman said the explosion occurred in <LOCATION> Kfar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falous <