<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The opposition socialists pulled ahead of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> on Monday in municipal elections viewed as a gauge of how well the scandal-ridden Liberal Democrats will fare in national elections. Women were expected to tilt the vote in favor of the opposition following a campaign that focused on a sex scandal in the governing party. With 47 of the 128 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> decided, the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had won 22, nine more than the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The early results were considered significant since the Socialists held only 11 assembly seats coming into Sunday's election The Liberal Democrats had 63. The Clean Government Party had five seats, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> three, and independent candidates had won four, the television network said. About 5.18 million people, or 58.7 percent of the eligible voters, cast ballots Sunday. That was up from 53.5 percent in the last election in 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> said. The election was being closely watched as a sign of how the Liberal Democrats, who have ruled <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> since 1954, will do in a national election July 23 for half the seats in the upper house of the parliament, or Diet. More than 61 percent of registered women voted, compared to 56.16 percent of men, the board said. The high turnout, espec